This project is split across three licensing boundaries to match
industry best practice for hypervisor-based security projects.

┌─────────────────────┬──────────────┬─────────────────────────────────┐
│ Directory           │ License      │ Reason                          │
├─────────────────────┼──────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
│ src/                │ Apache 2.0   │ Hypervisor core + detection     │
│ agent/              │ Apache 2.0   │ Userspace agents                │
│ tests/              │ Apache 2.0   │ Unit tests + benchmarks         │
│ loader/linux/       │ GPL v2       │ Linux kernel module requirement │
│ loader/windows/     │ Apache 2.0   │ Windows driver (no GPL needed)  │
│ loader/uefi/        │ Apache 2.0   │ UEFI loader                     │
└─────────────────────┴──────────────┴─────────────────────────────────┘

Why this split?

1. Apache 2.0 for the core — provides an explicit patent grant that
   protects both users and downstream distributors.  For a security
   project where contributors may hold patents on detection techniques,
   this grant is essential to avoid post-contribution patent litigation.

2. GPL v2 for the Linux loader — required.  The Linux kernel is
   licensed under GPL v2 and uses EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL for many symbols
   the loader needs.  A non-GPL module triggers kernel taint and is
   shunned by distribution maintainers.

3. Apache 2.0 for Windows and UEFI — these platforms do not impose
   GPL requirements on loadable drivers.  Apache 2.0 chosen for
   consistency with the core and its patent protection.

See:
  LICENSE-APACHE — Apache License 2.0 (applies to src/, agent/, tests/,
                   loader/windows/, loader/uefi/)
  LICENSE-GPL    — GNU General Public License v2 (applies to loader/linux/)

Individual source files contain SPDX-style identifiers in their headers
indicating which license governs them.

For the avoidance of doubt: files without an explicit license header
are governed by the Apache 2.0 license.
